    &gt; By your logic, it sounds as though one might as well do 
    &gt; away with the
    &gt; protected keyword, as well as default package access 
    &gt; behavior.  That is, you
    &gt; are saying that if class A&#39;s methods are accessible to 
    &gt; members of its
    &gt; package and subclasses or only its package, then what the 
    &gt; programmer should
    &gt; do is define the methods of class A as public.  You said 
    &gt; that &quot;if the client
    &gt; has no business touching these parts, make them private.&quot; 
    &gt;  But we should say
    &gt; that while a client can be an unknown, external process 
    &gt; or third party
    &gt; library, a client can also be a class in the same package 
    &gt; of our own
    &gt; library.  The existence of the various access modifiers 
    &gt; gives us finer
    &gt; control than the binary choice of public/private.
